  "prompt": "On a train in India, what does SL, 1A, 2A, 3A, 2S, CC mean?",
  "response": "In Indian Railways, the abbreviations **SL, 1A, 2A, 3A, 2S, and CC** refer to different classes of travel. Here's what they stand for:\n\n1. **SL (Sleeper Class)**:\n   - A non-AC, budget-friendly class with sleeping berths.\n   - Consists of 3-tier berths (lower, middle, upper) and is commonly used for long-distance travel.\n\n2. **1A (First AC)**:\n   - The most luxurious and expensive class.\n   - Air-conditioned coaches with 2-tier or 4-berth compartments, offering privacy and comfort.\n\n3. **2A (Second AC)**:\n   - Air-conditioned class with 2-tier berths (lower and upper).\n   - More affordable than 1A but still comfortable, with curtains for privacy.\n\n4. **3A (Third AC)**:\n   - Air-conditioned class with 3-tier berths (lower, middle, upper).\n   - Popular and affordable for long-distance travel, but less spacious than 2A.\n\n5. **2S (Second Sitting)**:\n   - Non-AC seating class with unreserved or reserved seats.\n   - Used for short-distance travel, with no air-conditioning or sleeping arrangements.\n\n6. **CC (AC Chair Car)**:\n   - Air-conditioned seating class with reserved seats.\n   - Common on short-distance or express trains, offering comfort for the duration of the journey.\n\nThese classes cater to different budgets and preferences, with varying levels of comfort and amenities.",
